			<header class="page-header">
				<h1 class="page-title">
					Honor Seminar				</h1>
							</header><!-- .page-header -->

						
				
<article id="post-706" class="post-706 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-core-classes-and-seminars tag-honors-seminar tag-leadership tag-speaker">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/hon-401-helps-bring-out-the-leader-in-you/" rel="bookmark">HON 401 Helps Bring Out the Leader in You</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/hon-401-helps-bring-out-the-leader-in-you/" title="Permalink to HON 401 Helps Bring Out the Leader in You" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T20:59:33+00:00">May 5, 2014</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-02-15T18:12:07+00:00">February 15, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div>
<div>
<p>Starting this spring, the Honors College introduced a new advanced Honors seminar—HON 401: Leadership, an extension of a previous seminar—that focuses on fostering leadership among Honors College students. Taught by Department of Managerial Studies Associate Professor Jenny Hoobler, the course guides students through leadership theory, research, and practice while attempting to uncover each student’s authentic leadership style. “I really want to get the point across to students that leaders come in all shapes, sizes, and variations,” says Professor Hoobler.</p>
<p>With guest speakers from organizations and businesses based in the Chicago area, students see first-hand how great leaders can be found in their own communities and are encouraged to tap into insights of leadership roles and perspectives. From leaders like Alderman Jason Ervin to the President and CEO of the Women’s Business Development Center Emilia Dimenco, the guest speakers fall nothing short of inspirational.</p>
<p>The three credit-hour course also gives students the time and opportunity to allow them to discover their own leadership potential. The class uses multi-factor leadership questionnaires to assess leadership potential and determine areas where students can improve. “I think it’s really important for students at this level to get that professional development and feedback,” states Professor Hoobler.</p>
<div id="attachment_707" style="width: 160px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.00.43-PM.png"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-707" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.00.43-PM.png" alt="Scott Dikkers, founding editor of The Onion, spoke to UIC students as part of the HON 401 Leadership Seminar." width="150" height="150" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Scott Dikkers, founding editor of The Onion, spoke to UIC students as part of the HON 401 Leadership Seminar.</p></div>
</div>
<div>
<p>Students’ professional development goes far beyond these assessments. Students also submit an article to a student academic journal of their choosing on a topic related to leadership towards the end of the semester.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<div>
<p>Professor Hoobler feels that her students are very interested and engaged in the class and adds that the chance for students to discuss their research questions is mutually beneficial. “That kind of environment where students are contributing and I’m sharing research that I really care about with them completely summarizes why I do this,” says Professor Hoobler. “It really gives me an intellectual charge to be able to do that. It’s the perfect environment for me, and I hope the students have benefitted from that as well.”</p>
<p>Professor Hoobler hopes to continue teaching this seminar, bringing in more community leaders who can inspire and help develop leaders among all Honors College students.</p>
<p><em>by: Francisca Corona, Sophomore, English</em></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-705" class="post-705 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-core-classes-and-seminars tag-honors-seminar tag-research-2">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/an-innovative-new-introduction-to-research-seminar/" rel="bookmark">An Innovative New “Introduction to Research” Seminar</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/an-innovative-new-introduction-to-research-seminar/" title="Permalink to An Innovative New “Introduction to Research” Seminar" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T20:45:43+00:00">May 5, 2014</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div>
<div>
<p>This spring semester the Honors College offered a new, innovative HON 201 seminar to introduce research to students who may not be able to take a research methods course in their own majors. As the instructor of HON 201: “Introduction to Research and Critical Thinking”, Dr. David McKirnan presented critical analyses of the scientific method to Honors College students.<br />
Dr. McKirnan—who has over 25 years of experience teaching psychology and performing his own research on health behavior and HIV—has noticed that some courses focus too much on “techniques and definitions;” for this reason, he designed this class to focus more on the general conceptual basis of articulating research questions, developing hypotheses, and gathering and evaluating evidence.</p>
<p>Studies of current college graduates show that they have not achieved the same levels of critical thinking abilities as prior generations did during their undergraduate education. To address this issue, Dr. McKirnan worked with Honors College Dean Bette Bottoms and Associate Dean Hui-Ching Chang on developing a critical thinking class centered on scientific research that could teach “thinking as much as content.” He hopes that someday this class will be integrated as one of the core Honors College courses, which he feels are indispensable for dynamic thinkers.</p>
</div>
<div>
<p>Dr. McKirnan believes that all UIC students should be able to analyze information and become sophisticated thinkers able to intelligently scrutinize their learning. Eventually students should be able to partake in scholarly conversations with professors and ask them how they support their content with evidence. He wants students to learn skills to be able to think critically about any problem—no matter the discipline—and to be able to gather and analyze evidence to test the validity of that idea.</p>
<p>This HON 201 course also teaches students about maximizing their research potential in regards to how to navigate the Institutional Review Board, find research funding, and work with professors and research mentors. Dr. McKirnan’s primary role in the Honors College is teaching and he is “continuously impressed” with Honors students’ discussions, feedback, and projects (e.g. the Honors Capstone, which he has mentored several times). Through his long and varied involvement with research and Honors students, Dr. McKirnan has come to appreciate the Honors College as one of UIC’s greatest strengths.</p>
<p><em>by Rafid Rahman, Freshman, Biological Sciences    </em></p>
</div>
</div>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
			
		
